canonical:
  title: 作小障子歌求仁齋妙筆
  author: 姜希孟
  language: lzh
  text: 君不見唐家有摩詰畫趣詩思兩奇絶又不見仁齋愛詩畫胷襟坦蕩參元化世上俗畫亦無數通神妙手誠難遇模形寫肉蠶㨾密畫骨於兄纔見一豈但傳神入毫素尤工萬里滄洲趣我有障子絶短小貼以蠻牋光皎皎爲我或作方壺圖僊曹遊戲靑雲衢爲我或作三湘曲平湖闊呑楚山綠雲冠霞帔氣欲活欹岸側島隨手抹若遣神圖侈文房隱几卧榻同滄浪滄浪我所愛擧首悵望塵埃內名韁役役苦覊絆夢繞江河渾未斷倘能座右對三峽何事江頭理歸楫
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 作小障子歌求仁齋妙筆
  author: 姜希孟
  language: lzh
  text: 君不見唐家有摩詰。畫趣詩思兩奇絶。又不見仁齋愛詩畫。胷襟坦蕩參元化。世上俗畫亦無數。通神妙手誠難遇。模形寫肉蠶㨾密。畫骨於兄纔見一。豈但傳神入毫素。尤工萬里滄洲趣。我有障子絶短小。貼以蠻牋光皎皎。爲我或作方壺圖。僊曹遊戲靑雲衢。爲我或作三湘曲。平湖闊呑楚山綠。雲冠霞帔氣欲活。欹岸側島隨手抹。若遣神圖侈文房。隱几卧榻同滄浪。滄浪我所愛。擧首悵望塵埃內。名韁役役苦覊絆。夢繞江河渾未斷。倘能座右對三峽。何事江頭理歸楫。
korean:
  title: 작소장자가 구인재묘필
  author: 강희맹
  language: kor
  text: |-
    그대는 보지 않는가 당대 왕마힐의
    화취와 시상이 둘 다 기절한 것을
    또 보지 않는가 인재가 시와 그림을 사랑하여
    호탕한 흉금이 조화에 참예함을
    세상에 속화들은 무수하여도
    신에 통한 묘수는 진실로 만나기 어렵네
    형상을 본뜨고 살을 그림은 누에처럼 많지만
    뼈를 그림은 오직 형에게서만 볼 뿐
    어찌 다만 붓 끝에 신을 전할 뿐이랴
    만리 창주의 의취를 더욱 잘 나타내네
    내가 가진 아주 조그만 장지
    왜지를 붙여서 빛이 새하얗네
    날 위하여 혹 방호도를 만들어 주소
    선신들이 청운 거리에서 유회하며
    날 위하여 혹 삼상곡을 그려 주소
    평평한 호수가 푸른 초산을 헌출히 삼기는
    구름관[冠]에 안개창의를 싱싱하게
    기운 언덕 딸린 섬을 멋대로 손가는 대로
    그대 신도 보내어서 내 문방을 꾸며주면
    책상이랑 탑이 창랑과 같아지리
    창랑은 내가 사랑하는 것
    머리 들어 진세를 서글피 바라보네
    공명의 굴레에 얽혀 허덕거리는 신세
    꿈은 강하에 들려 꿈은 노상 끊어지지 않네
    혹시 좌우에 삼협을 대할양이면
    하필 강가에서 고향 돌아갈 배를 손질하겠나
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_1400_010_0260&viewSync=OT
  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 방호도(方壺圖) : '
    value: 방호(方壺)는 신선이 사는 산의 이름이다.
english:
  title: 'A Song on the Small Folding Screen: Requesting Master Enjoin''s Brush'
  author: Gang Hee-meng
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Have you not seen the master Wang Mo of Tang,
    Whose painted charm and poetic vision both reached transcendence?
    Have you not seen how Enjoin loves both poem and painting,
    His open heart participating in heaven's transformations?

    Though vulgar paintings crowd the world in countless multitudes,
    The subtle hand that communes with the divine is truly rare to encounter.
    Many trace mere form and render flesh with silkworm-like precision,
    Yet the bones revealed in painting—these one sees only through the master.

    It is not merely transmitting spirit through the brush's tip,
    But capturing the distant mood of ten thousand miles of azure shores.
    I possess a folding screen, small and modest,
    Mounted on fine paper that gleams pure white.

    Would you for me perhaps paint the Palace of Fanghu,
    Where immortals wander and play along the clouded streets?
    Would you for me perhaps depict the triple Xiang song,
    Where broad waters swallow the green mountains whole?

    Cloud-crowned and mist-draped, the spirit seems to live,
    Skewed banks and scattered isles rendered by your spontaneous hand.
    If you send forth your divine brush to grace my humble study,
    Then my desk and couch shall become one with the river's song.

    The river's song—this I cherish above all.
    I lift my head and gaze mournfully through the dust of the world.
    Bound by the halter of fame, I labor in these fetters,
    Yet my dreams drift down the rivers, never quite breaking free.

    If only I could keep the Three Gorges before my seat,
    Why then should I trouble to prepare my boat for home?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Wang Mo (王摩詰), also known as Wang Wei, was a celebrated Tang Dynasty painter and poet renowned for his monochromatic landscape paintings and poetic sensibility.
  - key: ''
    value: Enjoin (仁齋) was the sobriquet of the patron for whom this screen was created, indicating someone of refined artistic taste.
  - key: ''
    value: The Palace of Fanghu (方壺) is a legendary mountain dwelling of the immortals, evoking themes of escape from worldly concerns.
  - key: ''
    value: The triple Xiang (三湘) refers to the three branches of the Xiang River in Hunan province, associated with melancholic beauty and distant longing.
  - key: ''
    value: The river's song (滄浪) carries resonance of both natural beauty and the poet's inner yearning for transcendence and simplicity.
